:INFO
1. The urge to breathe is CO2, not oxygen
Most beginners assume they're running out of air. They're not. The sensation is CO2 buildup \
triggering a reflex. Your O2 levels can still be fine while your body screams at you to surface. \
Once you understand that, everything changes. You stop fighting the wrong thing.

:INFO
2. Cold water on your face literally slows your heart
The mammalian dive reflex is structural, not trained. Cold water on the face triggers a cascade: \
heart rate drops, blood centralises to the core, the spleen contracts and dumps extra red blood \
cells into circulation. Warm pool water doesn't trigger it the same way. The sea is doing \
something the pool cannot.

:INFO
3. Equalization is a motor skill, not a concept
Frenzel technique moves air using the tongue and soft palate, not the chest. You can read a \
perfect description of it and still be completely unable to do it. It takes weeks to wire the \
movement. You cannot think your way into it.

:QUOTE
Equalization is a motor skill. You learn it with your body, not by reading about it.

:INFO
4. Freefall is real and it's the whole reason
Past the point of neutral buoyancy, somewhere around 10 to 15 metres depending on lung volume \
and wetsuit, you stop kicking. You just sink. No effort. Three seconds of falling in silence. \
It's the thing you keep going back for.

:INFO
5. Shallow water blackout is more dangerous than deep water blackout
Most freediving drownings happen in the last few metres of ascent. O2 partial pressure drops \
as you rise, and it can fall below the threshold for consciousness before you reach the surface. \
Deep water gives you time. The shallows don't. Never train alone.

:INFO
6. Most of the training happens out of the water
CO2 tolerance tables on a kitchen timer. Dry equalization practice in front of a mirror. \
Relaxation drills. Breath hold sessions in bed. The pool time is the test, not the training. \
Most people get this backwards.

:INFO
7. A 7mm wetsuit is not optional in cold water
Below 10 degrees, thermal protection stops being a comfort variable and becomes a safety variable. \
Cold impairs judgment and motor control before you notice it's happening. The shiver response \
costs oxygen. The 7mm is not gear snobbery.

:INFO
8. Your shoulders report on your anxiety
Tension in the shoulders means you're holding on somewhere. It's not a shoulder problem. \
It's a whole body bracing response to the situation. Coaches spot it from the surface. \
The dive starts falling apart from there.

:QUOTE
The shoulder thing is not a shoulder thing. It's a whole body holding on thing.

:INFO
9. The pool is nothing like the sea
Visibility, cold, current, pressure at depth, the full mammalian dive reflex trigger. \
All different. Open water introduces variables the pool eliminates. Pool training is necessary. \
It is not sufficient. Plan the sea trip before you think you're ready.

:NOTE
Shallow water blackout is the leading cause of drowning in recreational freediving. \
It occurs without warning. There is no sensation of losing consciousness. The only \
reliable prevention is a trained buddy watching from the surface at all times. \
Never freedive alone. Never.

